<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-using-reciprocals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Using Reciprocals</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.1 Real Numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Apply reciprocal of real numbers in mathematical computations</li>
            <li>Promote the use of real numbers in day-to-day activities</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/real-numbers/using-reciprocals.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/real-numbers/step-by-step-guide_using-reciprocals.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <p xml:id="auto_urf12wca">
        This is application of the concept of reciprocals to perform different types of mathematical operations such as division, solving equations, proportions, rates, and real-life problem-solving.
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>Work in groups</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    This anchor activity activates prior knowledge of reciprocals and explores their properties through hands-on group work. Students discover that multiplying a number by its reciprocal always gives 1.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Circulation Questions:</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>"What happens when you multiply a number by its reciprocal?"</li>
                        <li>"Can you find the reciprocal of zero? Why or why not?"</li>
                        <li>"How did you find the reciprocal of a decimal number like 0.25?"</li>
                        <li>"What pattern do you notice about the reciprocal of a fraction?"</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_utpinvge">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_kzdvgde2">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9wsv345w">
                In groups, find an exercise book and a pen.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ceoiawpr">
               1. Write different numbers (that is positive, negative, decimal numbers and fractions) on the exercise book.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_69nx3ewo">
                Example: <m>2, -4,0.25,\frac{5}{8}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_v1zwxxux">
                2. Find the reciprocals of the numbers you have formed.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hklf5t7v">
                Example: Number formed is <m>\frac{5}{8}</m> its reciprocal is given by <m>1 \div \frac{5}{8} = 1 \times \frac{8}{5} = \frac{8}{5}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_56pfncs4">
                3. Multiply the original number you formed by its corresponding reciprocal and observe the result.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ao98qjd7">
                Example: <m>\frac{5}{8} \times \frac{8}{5}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t312jtnb">
                4. Discuss cases where reciprocals do not exist.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ry3vuksw">
                5. Identify a real world problem where reciprocals are useful.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jyqeyk7p">
                6. Share your work with fellow learners.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>Whole class</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Formalize the three key applications of reciprocals in mathematical computations, using the insight content below.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Key Takeaways to Emphasize:</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Converting division into multiplication: <m>a \div b = a \times \frac{1}{b}</m></li>
                        <li>Solving equations: use the reciprocal to isolate the variable</li>
                        <li>Working with proportions, rates, and real-world problems</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The reciprocal of 0 does NOT exist (division by zero is undefined)</li>
                        <li>The reciprocal of a negative number is also negative</li>
                        <li>To find the reciprocal of a decimal, first convert to a fraction</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_shbolqtx">
        <p xml:id="auto_ywq44ufi">
           <alert>How reciprocals are used in mathematical computations:</alert> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1eux7g8p">
            <ol xml:id="auto_np887074">
                <li xml:id="auto_7iwmvixk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_aw8otj4t">
                        Converting Division into Multiplication
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_i6ysqeaz">
                        Instead of dividing a number, we multiply by the reciprocal: <m>a \div b = a \times \frac{1}{b}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_c0d4a1u4">
                        Example with whole numbers: 
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_2ycb2ftt">
                    <m>8 \div 2 = 8 \times \frac{1}{2} = 4</m> 
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_76g8as23">
                        Example with fractions: 
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_20lewqpz">
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\frac{5}{6} \div \frac{2}{3}=\amp \frac{5}{6} \times \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp \frac{15}{12}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{4} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_apjpbd0h">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zmoxblvu">
                        Solving Equations
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_syhqatra">
                    When solving equations where a variable is multiplied by a number, we use the reciprocal to isolate the variable.  
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_d65l63tp">
                        Example: Solve for <m>x</m> in the equation <m>3x = 12</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v0585prq">
                        To solve for <m>x</m>, multiply both sides by the reciprocal of <m>3</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_wdmvx3c6">
                        Therefore, <m>x = 12 \times \frac{1}{3} = 4</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_recqufey">
                    <p xml:id="auto_op92rcoh">
                        Working with proportions and ratios while cooking.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_y9srvp8x">
                    Example:  If a recipe uses <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> of a cup of sugar per serving, how many servings can you make with <m>4</m> cups?
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v1gbq9gz">
                        To find the number of servings, compute: <m>4 \div \frac{2}{3}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_e8iuzums">
                        <md>
                            <mrow>=\amp 4 \times \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp \frac{12}{2} </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \, 6 \text{ servings}</mrow> 
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>Individual work, then compare with a partner</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Work through the textbook examples on the board, showing how reciprocals are applied in real-world contexts (land division, investment doubling, speed calculations). Then assign independent practice.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Monitor learners as they work, ensuring they correctly convert division problems into multiplication by the reciprocal.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    
    
    <example xml:id="auto_y5hnafzy">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_b56x2zdi">
                Kerich is a farmer and has <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> of an acre of land and wants to divide it into plots of <m>\frac{1}{6}</m> acre each. How many plots can Kerich make?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_4ekiijor">
              To find the number of plots that Kerich can make, we solve it as a division problem.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_u8v04zvf">
                Divide <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> by <m>\frac{1}{6}</m> and solve it by multiplying <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> by the reciprocal of <m>\frac{1}{6}</m> as below:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gz20nkbb">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{2}{3} \div \frac{1}{6}=\amp \frac{2}{3} \times \frac{6}{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{12}{3}=\amp 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_teu6vceq">
                Hence Kerich can make <m>4</m> plots.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
         <p xml:id="auto_sp9xwml3">
            A printing machine can print <m>\frac{5}{6}</m> of a book page per second. 
                        How long will it take to print <m>20</m> pages?
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
                    <p xml:id="auto_rzip5tn8">
                        If <m>1</m> second = <m>\frac{5}{6}</m> of a page, then for <m>20</m> pages, we calculate as follows:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v7eht6tj">
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \text{ Time } =\amp 20 \div \frac{5}{6}</mrow> 
                            <mrow>=\amp 20 \times \frac{6}{5}</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_d9v0r4jj">
                        Multiplying and simplifying we have: Time = <m>\frac{120}{5} = 24</m> seconds.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_5ou5vijq">
                        Thus, the printing machines will take <m>24</m> seconds to print <m>20</m> pages.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_catjfljd">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_tfo65jlj">
                Njoki, a business woman invest ksh <m>5\,000</m> in a business that promises to double his investment every <m>1.5</m> years.
                What fraction of her initial investment will she have after <m>4.5</m> years?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_rbuqf5hs">
                If <m>1.5</m> years <m>= 2</m> times the initial investment, how about <m>4.5</m> years?
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ev1dktau">
                Computing the number of times her investment will yield after <m>4.5</m> years we have: <m>4.5 \div 1.5</m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hw1vxwqk">
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4.5 \times \frac{1}{1.5}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jv23lhs1">
              This means her investment will double <m>3</m> times.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gj66g62b">
              Therefore, after <m>4.5</m> years her investment will be <m>5000 \times 2\times2\times2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_go9elhlq">
                <md>
                    <mrow>= \amp 5000 \times 8</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 40\,000 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gjryfevn">
                <alert>Illustration</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_uh8qp2m6">
               Representing the number of years with their corresponding double investment in ksh makes it easier to understand the above computations.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_afcmem3m">
                Remember at the start of a period we will represent it with a <m>0</m>.
            </p>
            <tabular>
                <row >
                    <cell >Years:</cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1.5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4.5</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Shillings:</cell>
                    <cell><m>5\,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>10\,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>20\,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\rightarrow</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>40\,000</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_x3kx4obw">
                Hence Njoki will have ksh <m>40\,000</m> after <m>4.5</m> years.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
     <example xml:id="auto_1bb1jvi6">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_pladrpvt">
              Okoth runs <m>3 \frac{1}{4}</m>  miles in <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> an hour. What is her speed in miles per hour?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_utsdx26k">
                To find speed we divide distance by time such that: speed = <m>\frac{\text{ distance}}{\text{ time}}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a9v6osv8">
                First, we need to convert the fraction <m>3\frac{1}{4}</m> into an improper fraction which is <m>\frac{13}{4}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0540l9oy">
               Hence,  speed = <m>3\frac{1}{4} \div \frac{1}{2} = \frac{13}{4} \div \frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_1qtiawc6">
                Multiply <m>\frac{13}{4}</m> by the reciprocal of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_dskwsgxq">
                 <m>\frac{13}{4} \times \frac{2}{1} = \frac{26}{4}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_24p80mvf">
                Simplifying <m>\frac{26}{4}</m> we get <m>\frac{13}{2}</m> which is <m>= 6 \frac{1}{2}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment – Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>5 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>Individual</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Students complete the checkpoint and exercise questions individually to demonstrate understanding of using reciprocals in computations.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify common misconceptions for the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
